/*
You want the maximum-speed OpenMP batch-dump (where threads write to private RAM arrays and dump to a file at the end), but you want the chunks to strictly snap to Line Feed (LF) boundaries so there is zero overlap math, zero duplicate checking, and absolutely no chance of a match bleeding across a newline.

This actually simplifies the OpenMP logic beautifully. Because we force the threads to strictly evaluate isolated physical lines, we completely eliminate the need for the messy "overlap" parameter from the previous multi-threaded code.

Here is the ultimate, max-speed, LF-bounded batch extractor.
*/

/*
Why this architecture is bulletproof for your use case:
Zero Duplication Risk: Because adj_start and adj_end perfectly slice the file on \n boundaries, no two threads will ever look at the same physical line. The strict_end checks from the previous code are gone because they are no longer necessary.

Isolated Levenshtein Matrix: The fuzzy search engine now completely resets its state at the beginning of every physical line (prev_col[idx] = (int)idx). This ensures that a 1-character typo at the end of Line 1 does not magically combine with a typo at the beginning of Line 2 to create a false positive.

memmem Safety: The exact match logic is now fed the exact length of the current line (remaining = line_len). It literally cannot return an offset that exists past the newline character.
*/

// Max-Speed LF-Bounded Batch Extractor [[[
#define _GNU_SOURCE
#include <omp.h>
//#include <string.h>
//#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdint.h>
//#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdbool.h>
// M ]]]

// "Efialtis - Audio Spectrum Extravaganza" [
// gcc -O3 -fopenmp -o Efialtis playwav_opengl_visualizer_openMP.c kissfft-master/kiss_fftr.c kissfft-master/kiss_fft.c -lglfw -lGL -lasound -lm

